# Linux Commands Cheat Sheet

A practical beginner-to-advanced Linux command reference with examples.

## 1) Basic Navigation
`pwd` — Show current directory  
Example: `pwd` "present working directory"

`ls` — List files and folders  
Example: `ls`

`ls -la` — List all files, including hidden ones  
Example: `ls -la`

`cd /path/to/folder` — Change directory  
Example: `cd /var/log`

`cd ..` — Move one folder up  
Example: `cd ..`

`cd ~` — Go to home directory  
Example: `cd ~`

`clear` — Clear terminal screen  
Example: `clear`

## 2) File and Directory Management
`touch file.txt` — Create an empty file  
Example: `touch notes.txt`

`mkdir test` — Create a folder  
Example: `mkdir project`

`mkdir -p a/b/c` — Create nested folders  
Example: `mkdir -p app/src/components`

`cp file1.txt file2.txt` — Copy file  
Example: `cp notes.txt backup.txt`

`cp -r dir1 dir2` — Copy folder recursively  
Example: `cp -r project project-backup`

`mv old.txt new.txt` — Rename or move file  
Example: `mv draft.txt final.txt`

`rm file.txt` — Delete file  
Example: `rm temp.txt`

`rm -r folder` — Delete folder recursively  
Example: `rm -r old-project`

`find . -name "file.txt"` — Find a file by name  
Example: `find . -name "config.json"`

`stat file.txt` — Show file details  
Example: `stat notes.txt`

`file file.txt` — Detect file type  
Example: `file script.sh`

## 3) Viewing File Content
`cat file.txt` — Show full file content  
Example: `cat notes.txt`

`less file.txt` — View file page by page  
Example: `less large.log`

`head -n 20 file.txt` — Show first 20 lines  
Example: `head -n 20 app.log`

`tail -n 20 file.txt` — Show last 20 lines  
Example: `tail -n 20 app.log`

`tail -f app.log` — Watch log file live  
Example: `tail -f /var/log/system.log`

`wc -l file.txt` — Count lines in file  
Example: `wc -l users.txt`

## 4) Editing Text Files
`nano file.txt` — Edit file with nano  
Example: `nano notes.txt`

`vim file.txt` — Edit file with vim  
Example: `vim notes.txt`

`sort file.txt` — Sort lines  
Example: `sort names.txt`

`uniq file.txt` — Remove adjacent duplicate lines  
Example: `uniq names.txt`

`cut -d':' -f1 /etc/passwd` — Cut first field using `:` delimiter  
Example: `cut -d':' -f1 /etc/passwd`

`tr 'a-z' 'A-Z' < file.txt` — Convert lowercase to uppercase  
Example: `tr 'a-z' 'A-Z' < names.txt`

`sed -n '1,10p' file.txt` — Print selected lines  
Example: `sed -n '1,10p' notes.txt`

`awk '{print $1}' file.txt` — Print first column  
Example: `awk '{print $1}' data.txt`

## 5) Permissions and Ownership
`chmod 644 file.txt` — Set read/write permissions  
Example: `chmod 644 notes.txt`

`chmod +x script.sh` — Make script executable  
Example: `chmod +x deploy.sh`

`chown user:user file.txt` — Change owner and group  
Example: `sudo chown karan:staff notes.txt`

`umask` — Show default permissions mask  
Example: `umask`

## 6) User and System Information
`whoami` — Show current user  
Example: `whoami`

`id` — Show user and group IDs  
Example: `id`

`uname -a` — Show system information  
Example: `uname -a`

`hostname` — Show host name  
Example: `hostname`

`uptime` — Show uptime and load  
Example: `uptime`

`date` — Show current date and time  
Example: `date`

`cal` — Show calendar  
Example: `cal`

`history` — Show command history  
Example: `history`

## 7) Process and Resource Monitoring
`ps aux` — Show running processes  
Example: `ps aux | grep nginx`

`top` — Live process monitor  
Example: `top`

`htop` — Better process monitor if installed  
Example: `htop`

`pidof nginx` — Show process ID by name  
Example: `pidof nginx`

`kill 1234` — Kill process by PID  
Example: `kill 1234`

`kill -9 1234` — Force kill process  
Example: `kill -9 1234`

`pkill nginx` — Kill process by name  
Example: `pkill nginx`

`jobs` — Show background jobs  
Example: `jobs`

`bg` — Resume job in background  
Example: `bg`

`fg` — Bring job to foreground  
Example: `fg`

`free -h` — Show memory usage  
Example: `free -h`

`df -h` — Show disk usage  
Example: `df -h`

`du -sh folder` — Show folder size  
Example: `du -sh Downloads`

`lscpu` — Show CPU info  
Example: `lscpu`

`lsblk` — Show block devices  
Example: `lsblk`

`vmstat 1` — Show system performance stats  
Example: `vmstat 1`

## 8) Networking Commands
`ip a` — Show IP addresses  
Example: `ip a`

`ip route` — Show routing table  
Example: `ip route`

`ss -tulpn` — Show listening ports  
Example: `ss -tulpn`

`ping google.com` — Check connectivity  
Example: `ping google.com`

`curl https://example.com` — Fetch web page content  
Example: `curl https://example.com`

`wget https://example.com/file` — Download file  
Example: `wget https://example.com/file.zip`

`nslookup google.com` — DNS lookup  
Example: `nslookup google.com`

`dig google.com` — Detailed DNS query  
Example: `dig google.com`

`traceroute google.com` — Show network path  
Example: `traceroute google.com`

`netstat -tulpn` — Show open ports using older tool  
Example: `netstat -tulpn`

## 9) Archives and Compression
`tar -cvf files.tar folder/` — Create tar archive  
Example: `tar -cvf backup.tar project/`

`tar -xvf files.tar` — Extract tar archive  
Example: `tar -xvf backup.tar`

`tar -czvf files.tar.gz folder/` — Create compressed archive  
Example: `tar -czvf backup.tar.gz project/`

`tar -xzvf files.tar.gz` — Extract compressed archive  
Example: `tar -xzvf backup.tar.gz`

`zip -r archive.zip folder/` — Create zip archive  
Example: `zip -r project.zip project/`

`unzip archive.zip` — Extract zip archive  
Example: `unzip project.zip`

## 10) Package Management
### Debian / Ubuntu
`apt update` — Update package list  
Example: `sudo apt update`

`apt install nginx` — Install package  
Example: `sudo apt install nginx`

`apt remove nginx` — Remove package  
Example: `sudo apt remove nginx`

### RHEL / CentOS / Fedora
`yum install nginx` — Install package with yum  
Example: `sudo yum install nginx`

`dnf install nginx` — Install package with dnf  
Example: `sudo dnf install nginx`

### Arch Linux
`pacman -S nginx` — Install package with pacman  
Example: `sudo pacman -S nginx`

## 11) Services and Logs
`systemctl status nginx` — Check service status  
Example: `systemctl status nginx`

`systemctl start nginx` — Start service  
Example: `sudo systemctl start nginx`

`systemctl stop nginx` — Stop service  
Example: `sudo systemctl stop nginx`

`systemctl restart nginx` — Restart service  
Example: `sudo systemctl restart nginx`

`systemctl enable nginx` — Enable service at boot  
Example: `sudo systemctl enable nginx`

`journalctl -u nginx` — Show service logs  
Example: `journalctl -u nginx`

`journalctl -xe` — Show recent system errors  
Example: `journalctl -xe`

## 12) Disk and Storage
`mount` — Show mounted filesystems  
Example: `mount`

`mount /dev/sdb1 /mnt` — Mount a device  
Example: `sudo mount /dev/sdb1 /mnt`

`umount /mnt` — Unmount a device  
Example: `sudo umount /mnt`

`fdisk -l` — List partitions  
Example: `sudo fdisk -l`

`mkfs.ext4 /dev/sdb1` — Format partition as ext4  
Example: `sudo mkfs.ext4 /dev/sdb1`

`blkid` — Show filesystem UUIDs  
Example: `blkid`

## 13) SSH and Remote Access
`ssh user@server` — Connect to remote machine  
Example: `ssh karan@192.168.1.10`

`scp file.txt user@server:/tmp` — Copy file to server  
Example: `scp notes.txt karan@192.168.1.10:/tmp`

`scp user@server:/tmp/file.txt .` — Copy file from server  
Example: `scp karan@192.168.1.10:/tmp/notes.txt .`

`rsync -av folder/ backup/` — Sync folders efficiently  
Example: `rsync -av project/ backup/`

## 14) Advanced and Powerful Commands
`grep -R "searchterm" .` — Search recursively inside files  
Example: `grep -R "TODO" .`

`grep -n "main" file.txt` — Show matching lines with line numbers  
Example: `grep -n "error" app.log`

`xargs -n1 echo < list.txt` — Turn input into command arguments  
Example: `cat files.txt | xargs -n1 echo`

`tee output.txt` — Save output to file and also print it  
Example: `ls | tee files.txt`

`watch -n 2 df -h` — Run command every 2 seconds  
Example: `watch -n 2 df -h`

`nohup python app.py &` — Keep process running after terminal closes  
Example: `nohup python app.py &`

`screen` — Start screen session  
Example: `screen`

`screen -r` — Reattach screen session  
Example: `screen -r`

`tmux` — Start tmux session  
Example: `tmux`

`tmux attach` — Reattach tmux session  
Example: `tmux attach`

`crontab -e` — Edit cron jobs  
Example: `crontab -e`

`crontab -l` — List cron jobs  
Example: `crontab -l`

`env` — Show environment variables  
Example: `env`

`export VAR=value` — Set environment variable  
Example: `export NODE_ENV=production`

`alias ll='ls -la'` — Create shell shortcut  
Example: `alias ll='ls -la'`

`source ~/.bashrc` — Reload shell config  
Example: `source ~/.bashrc`

## 15) Dangerous Commands — Be Careful
`rm -rf folder/` — Delete folder and everything inside it  
Example: `rm -rf old-backup/`

`chmod -R 777 folder/` — Give full permissions to everyone  
Example: `chmod -R 777 shared-folder/`

`dd if=/dev/zero of=file.img bs=1M count=100` — Create large dummy file  
Example: `dd if=/dev/zero of=test.img bs=1M count=100`

`shutdown -h now` — Shut down system immediately  
Example: `sudo shutdown -h now`

`reboot` — Reboot system  
Example: `sudo reboot`

## Tip
Start with sections 1 to 5 if you are new to Linux.  
Use sections 6 to 15 as you get more comfortable.
